<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="129" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="129">China (Tibet, Yunnan).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="129" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="129">
The species name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhao &amp; Badano &amp; Liu" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Coniopterygidae" genus="Coniopteryx" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coniopteryx tenuisetosa" order="Raphidioptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuisetosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Coniopteryx tenuisetosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="“thin-haired”">&quot;thin-haired&quot;</normalizedToken>
is a composed adjective of Latin derivation, referring to the thin setae on the distal portion of gonocoxites 10.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="129" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="129">
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kis" authorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Coniopterygidae" genus="Coniopteryx" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coniopteryx (Coniopteryx) aspoecki" order="Raphidioptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspoecki" subGenus="Coniopteryx">Coniopteryx (Coniopteryx) aspoecki</taxonomicName>
Kis, 1967, but the two species differ in configuration of the male genitalia. In particular, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhao &amp; Badano &amp; Liu" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Coniopterygidae" genus="Coniopteryx" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coniopteryx (Coniopteryx) tenuisetosa" order="Raphidioptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenuisetosa" subGenus="Coniopteryx">Coniopteryx (Coniopteryx) tenuisetosa</taxonomicName>
is characterized by a short, not prominent terminal process of sternite 9 in lateral view, while it is prominent and arched in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. aspoecki" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspoecki">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">C. aspoecki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, in the new species, the distal portion of gonocoxites 10 is relatively robust and serrated, while in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. aspoecki" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspoecki">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">C. aspoecki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is thin, apically tapered and smooth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
